  "insights": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Modern methods account for more of demand, even as total demand stays stable",
        "body": "Among currently married and sexually active women aged 15 to 49, total demand for family planning was 71.1 percent in 2025, nearly the same as 70.7 percent in 2022. Unmet need was also nearly unchanged, at 12.5 percent. The clearer shift is in modern-method satisfaction: modern methods satisfied 62.5 percent of total demand in 2025, up from 59.1 percent in 2022, while met need for modern methods rose from 41.8 to 44.5 percent."
      },
      {
        "heading": "The same regional divide appears, but the stakes are larger",
        "body": "BARMM again stands out, with unmet need at 29.2 percent and modern-method demand satisfaction at 37.2 percent. Ilocos Region had the lowest unmet need at 6.6 percent, while MIMAROPA and Davao Region had the highest modern satisfaction at 75.0 and 73.2 percent. This is not just a higher-denominator version of the all-women page; the same geographic pattern becomes more consequential when the population is women with more immediate exposure to pregnancy."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Unmet need is concentrated among the youngest women in this denominator",
        "body": "The age pattern is unusually sharp. Women aged 15-19 had total demand of 81.1 percent, but unmet need of 38.5 percent and modern satisfaction of only 41.9 percent. By ages 30-34 and 35-39, unmet need falls to 12.1 and 10.8 percent, while modern satisfaction rises to 64.5 and 65.0 percent. The youngest group therefore has high demand but much weaker demand satisfaction."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Modern satisfaction is lower among women with no schooling and upper secondary schooling",
        "body": "Educational differences are not a straight line. Women with no education had modern-method demand satisfaction of 52.1 percent, and women with Grades 11-12 had 58.7 percent. Women with Grades 1-6 and Grades 7-10 were higher, at 67.1 and 65.6 percent. Unmet need was also highest among women with no education, at 24.4 percent, but Grades 11-12 also had elevated unmet need at 19.1 percent."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Wealth differences are clearer for modern use than for unmet need",
        "body": "Modern-method use declines across wealth groups, from 48.6 percent in the lowest quintile to 37.7 percent in the highest. Modern satisfaction also falls from 64.5 percent in the lowest quintile and 64.9 percent in the second quintile to 58.7 percent in the highest. Unmet need does not follow as clean a gradient: it is highest in the lowest quintile at 16.3 percent, but the fourth quintile is at 12.1 percent, above the middle quintile at 10.9 percent."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Total demand among currently married and sexually active women was stable, but modern methods satisfied more of that demand in 2025.",
      "BARMM remains the clearest regional outlier, combining very high unmet need with the lowest modern-method demand satisfaction.",
      "The youngest women in this denominator have high demand but much weaker demand satisfaction than women in their thirties."
    ]
  }
}
